<h1>Hotel Operations Automation:<br />Why It's Become Unavoidable</h1>

<p>Check-in/check-out processes in hotels <strong>average 12 minutes</strong>. Consider a boutique hotel with 40 rooms: reservations come in through 3 channels — OTAs, direct website, and phone. With manual management, double bookings are inevitable. Every double booking is both lost revenue and a guest dissatisfaction event.</p>

<h2>The 5 Biggest Time Wasters in Hospitality</h2>

<h3>1. Reservation notifications and confirmations</h3>
<p>Sending a manual confirmation email, reminder, and check-in information for every reservation takes hours. Automation: all of this communication flow runs automatically.</p>

<h3>2. Pre-arrival guest information collection</h3>
<p>Arrival time, special requests, vehicle information — collecting these requires a separate email chain. With a standard form flow, this information is collected automatically.</p>

<h3>3. Double booking management</h3>
<p>If reservations from different channels aren't updated in real time, double bookings occur. Centralized channel management eliminates this risk.</p>

<h3>4. Housekeeping coordination</h3>
<p>Communicating checkout information to the housekeeping team requires an additional communication step. Automation: checkout complete → housekeeping task automatically assigned.</p>

<h3>5. Post-stay review requests</h3>
<p>Review collection after checkout is either done manually or forgotten. Automatic review request flows increase TripAdvisor and Google review counts.</p>

